AI Framework

Data Scientists Use Machine Learning

\[X=\mbox{Input}\] \[f(X)=\mbox{Do Something to Input}\]

\[y=\mbox{Observed Output}\]

\[y=f(X)+\epsilon\]

Breaking This Down

\[y=f(X)+\epsilon\]

  • \(y\) can be: Numbers or Categories
  • \(X\) can be anything we can quantify
  • \(f(X)\) is largely unknown but perhaps assumed/tested

Evaluating Model

  • \(y\) is a number \(\sum(\hat{y}-y)^2\)

  • \(y\) is a category, cross-entropy, accuracy, etc.

  • Train/Test Split

Naive Model

  • Gotta beat this
  • \(f(X)= \mbox{CH if CH is Cheaper, else MM}\)
OJ.mod<-OJ%>%mutate(Cheap=ifelse(PriceDiff>0,"CH","MM"))
sum(OJ.mod$Purchase==OJ.mod$Cheap)/nrow(OJ.mod)

Logistic Regression - Blocking and Tackling

  • Moderately Interpretable

  • Not controversial

  • Must a-priori choose features

Model Building/Testing

set.seed(430)
default_idx = createDataPartition(OJ$Purchase, p = 0.75, list = FALSE)
default_trn = OJ[default_idx, ]
default_tst = OJ[-default_idx, ]

default_glm_mod = train(
  form = Purchase ~ .,
  data = default_trn,
  trControl = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5),
  method = "glm",
  family = "binomial"
)

LDA

  • Assume distribution for each class

  • Find how likely it is that the new data comes from each class, classify to highest probability

  • For two classes gives similar/same results as Logistic Regression

lda.fit <- train(Purchase ~ ., data=default_trn, method="lda")

LDA Fit

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, default_tst,type="prob")
lda.pred$Purchase<-ifelse(lda.pred$CH>0.5,"CH","MM")
pred.tab<-table(lda.pred$Purchase, default_tst$Purchase)
#pred.tab
(pred.tab[1,1]+pred.tab[2,2])/sum(pred.tab)
## [1] 0.8576779

Bagging Algorithms

  • Take many training sets from population

  • Build seperate prediction models using each training set

  • Average the resulting predictions

\[ \hat{f}(x)= \frac{1}{B} \sum_{b=1} \hat{f}^b(x)\] - Random Forest is most popular

Random Forest

control <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=10, repeats=3)
metric <- "Accuracy"
mtry <- sqrt(ncol(default_trn)-1)
tunegrid <- expand.grid(.mtry=mtry)
rf_default <- train(Purchase~., data=default_trn, method="rf", metric=metric, tuneGrid=tunegrid, trControl=control)
rf.pred <- predict(rf_default, default_tst,type="prob")
rf.pred$Purchase<-ifelse(rf.pred$CH>0.5,"CH","MM")
pred.tab<-table(rf.pred$Purchase, default_tst$Purchase)
#pred.tab
(pred.tab[1,1]+pred.tab[2,2])/sum(pred.tab)
## [1] 0.8127341

Boosting Algorithms

  • Combine a bunch of weak learners to make a strong learner

  • Built sequentially by fitting trees to residuals

  • Requires multiple tuning parameters (user supplied information)

  • AdaBoost is most popular

AdaBoost

fitGrid_2 <- expand.grid(mfinal = (1:3)*3,        
                         maxdepth = c(1, 3),      
                         coeflearn = c("Breiman")) 

fitControl_2 <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", 
                             number = 2, 
                             repeats = 1)
ada.fit <- train(Purchase ~ ., data=default_trn, method="AdaBoost.M1", trControl = fitControl_2,
  tuneGrid = fitGrid_2)

ada.pred <- predict(ada.fit, default_tst)
pred.tab<-table(ada.pred, default_tst$Purchase)
#pred.tab
(pred.tab[1,1]+pred.tab[2,2])/sum(pred.tab)
## [1] 0.82397

\(y=f(X)+\epsilon\)

  • \(X\) is anything that can be represented by a number - Factors, Images, Words
  • \(y\) is a number - Regression framework
  • \(y\) is one of several factors (good, bad, ugly) - One hot encoding
  • Data availability for \(X\) and \(y\) determine choices for technique
  • Many off-the-shelt techniques require tuning/user input
  • Interpretability vs Prediction

Data Science Done Wrong

Errors

Types of Errors:
- Question Errors
- Interpretation Errors
- Process Errors
- Application Errors

Patrick Surry and Nick Radcliffe

Question Errors

  • Correct/properly scoped question
  • Failure to include required constraints

Interpretation Errors

  • Data must be accurate
  • Data must mean what you think it means

Process Errors

  • Model and method assumptions must be validated.
  • Shortcuts dont usually pay off

Application Errors

  • Overfitting of training data
  • Misunderstanding of methodology

Biases

Types of Bias:
- Sample Bias
- Exclusion Bias
- Observer Bias
- Confounding Bias
- Measurement Bias

Salma Ghoneim / Catalogue of Bias

Sample Bias

  • Issue:
    • Data used for building the model doesnt represent the operational environment
  • Population vs.Sample
  • Fix:
    • Choose a representative sample
    • Unbiased sampling method
    • Large enough sample size
  • Rare events

Exclusion Bias

  • Issue:
    • Removing potentially important features in the name of “cleaning”
  • Fix:
    • Clean only whats necessary
    • Fully understand features

Observer Bias

  • Issue:
    • We tend to see what we expect to see
  • Fix:
    • Procedures for data collection and handling
    • Intellectual honesty

Confounding Bias

  • Issue:
    • Suggesting an association where there is none or masking a true association
  • Nightlight vs.Myopia
  • Fix:
    • Random assignment
    • Complete consideration of features

Measurement Bias

  • Issue:
    • Device(s) used for measurement alter data in some way
  • Fix:
    • Understand data collection mechanisms
    • Multiple measuring devices
    • Training on the use of devices

Current Research that May be of Interest

Early Warning Project

  • Identifying historical episodes of state- and non-state-led mass killing

  • Compiling data of potential “predictors” or “risk factors”

  • Training different statistical algorithms on historical data (1945 to 2015) to identify a model that performs well predicting onset of mass killing within the training set

  • Testing alternative models and selecting one that maximizes accuracy

  • Logistic Regression with Elastic Net regularizing (30 Variables)

  • In R this can be done model<-glmnet(x,y,family="binomial",alpha=value)

Early Warning Project

  • Results indicate that eight out of every ten countries that later experienced a new onset of mass killing had risk estimates of greater than 4 percent

  • Afghanistan, Yemen, Pakistan, S. Sudan, Congo, Egypt, Sudan, Somalia, Cameroon, Ethiopia

  • Early warning project, https://earlywarningproject.ushmm.org/

Bayesian Hierarchical Model for Criminal Investigations

  • Framework for assessing probability of attacks

  • Based off of observed intel, probability of being in given state

  • A Bayesian Hierarchical Model for Criminal Investigations, 2019 - Bunnin, Smith

Crime Predictions (DOJ Sponsored)

  • Winning Entry

\[ P_j(\tau,m)= \alpha + \sum_{i:c_i=j} h_{m,m_i}(t-t_i; \beta)\] - Locations where crimes occur have short term probability of future crimes occuring in same location or nearby

  • Self-Exciting Point Processes

  • Rotational grid, PAI-maximizing crime forecasts, 2018 - Mohler, Porter

Some Recommendations

  • What question are you trying to answer?
  • How is this measured?
  • What data have you collected to support that decision making process?
  • What can serve as a proxy if data is not available?
  • What decisions are you making?
  • Until these questions are answered, data science can do little to help
